The table itself is by default not responsible for borders in iText7, the cells are. You need to set every cell to be borderless if you want a borderless table (or set the outer cells to have no border on the edge if you still want inside borders).

    Cell cell = new Cell();
    cell.add(&quot;contents go here&quot;);
    cell.setBorder(Border.NO_BORDER);
    table.addCell(cell);

You could write a method which runs though all children of a Table and sets NO_BORDER.

    private static void RemoveBorder(Table table)
    {
        for (IElement iElement : table.getChildren()) {
            ((Cell)iElement).setBorder(Border.NO_BORDER);
        }
    }

This gives you the advantage that you can still use 

    table.add(&quot;whatever&quot;);
    table.add(&quot;whatever&quot;);
    RemoveBorder(table);

instead of changing it on all cells manual.

An utility function I define in my java code bases is the following:


    private static void setInnerCellBorder(Table table, Border border) {
        for (IElement child : table.getChildren()) {
            if (child instanceof Cell) {
                ((Cell) child).setBorder(border);
            }
        }
    }

Then if you want no borders you can call the function as follows: 

    setInnerCellBorder(table, Border.NO_BORDER);
    // or if you want a different color size you can do 
    setInnerCellBorder(Table, new SolidBorder(ColorConstants.RED, 2));

Since Java 9 [Matcher.replaceAll(Function)][1] is available on the [Matcher class][2]. If you want to do some extra transformation on the matched groups, then you can do something like this:

    import java.util.regex.Pattern;

    public class Playground {

        public static void main(String[] args) {
            String input = &quot;xDLMContent &lt;matches&gt; something &lt;and&gt; dSecurityGroup &lt;contains&gt; somethingelse &lt;and&gt; xDLMSomeOtherMetaDataField &lt;matches&gt; anothersomethingelse&quot;;
            String output = Pattern.compile(&quot;[dx]([A-Z][a-zA-Z]+)&quot;).matcher(input).replaceAll(m -&gt; transformation(m.group(1)));
            System.out.println(output);
        }

        public static String transformation(String input) {
            return input.concat(&quot;-extra&quot;);
        }
    }

This will print:

    DLMContent-extra &lt;matches&gt; something &lt;and&gt; SecurityGroup-extra &lt;contains&gt; somethingelse &lt;and&gt; DLMSomeOtherMetaDataField-extra &lt;matches&gt; anothersomethingelse

Some more info:
- `m.group()` gives you the whole matched value: `[dx]([A-Z][a-zA-Z]+)` for example `xDLMContent` 
- `m.group(1)` gives you the first group of the matched value: `([A-Z][a-zA-Z]+)` for example `DLMContent`

If you don&#39;t need the additional transformation, then you can just do: 

    .replaceAll(m -&gt; m.group(1))

  [1]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/regex/Matcher.html#replaceAll-java.util.function.Function-
  [2]: https://docs.oracle.com/javase/9/docs/api/java/util/regex/Matcher.html

